          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "This change was necessitated by many external factors, from government regulations to a fuel crisis to changing consumer demand. As a result, we're most fascinated by the early urethane bumper cars.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2020/10/vert2.jpg",
        "width": 1920,
        "height": 871,
        "caption": "Image Via Classic Auto Mall"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "From 1973 to 1976, we saw the Corvette lose its chrome bumpers, its big block, and even its convertible body style. While late impact-bumper C3 Corvettes are relatively common, stumbling upon 1974 and 1975 convertibles is a rare treat.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "At the time, there was a real concern that the US government would outlaw convertibles due to safety concerns. As a result, most domestic manufacturers stopped building them.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2020/10/vert3.jpg",
        "width": 1920,
        "height": 1231,
        "caption": "Image Via Classic Auto Mall"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Just 5,474 Corvette convertibles were built in 1974, which was also the final year of the 454 big block and the first year for a urethane rear bumper. 1973 Corvettes already had a urethane front bumper, but 1974 completed the look with a new rear end treatment. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "1974 Corvette rear bumpers are unique in that they're a two-piece affair, with a visible seam running vertically through the center. The following year would see this setup replaced with the one-piece unit that would last until the end of C3 production in 1982.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
